Introduce a shift y \to y - cx^2 to couple y with x^2. The integration measure remains unchanged (dy):\begin{aligned}
    \sqrt{2\pi} &= \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \exp\left[-\frac{1}{2}(y - cx^2)^2\right] dy \\
    &= \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}y^2 + cyx^2 - \frac{1}{2}c^2 x^4\right) dy \\
    &= \exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}c^2 x^4\right) \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}y^2 + cyx^2\right) dy
\end{aligned}

Rearranging to isolate the quartic term:\exp\left(\frac{1}{2}c^2 x^4\right) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \exp\left(-\frac{1}{2}y^2 + cyx^2\right) dy

Substitute the above identity into the original integral I = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \exp(-ax^2 + bx^4) dx:\begin{aligned}
    I &= \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} e^{-ax^2} \left[ \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} e^{-\frac{1}{2}y^2 + \sqrt{2b}\,x^2 y} dy \right] dx \\
      &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} dy \, e^{-\frac{1}{2}y^2} \underbrace{\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} dx \, \exp\left[ -\left(a - y\sqrt{2b}\right)x^2 \right]}_{\text{Gaussian integral over } x}
\end{aligned}

The partition function Z in the saddle point approximation is given by:Z \approx e^{-\Phi(y_0)} \sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{\Phi''(y_0)}}

The dimensionless Free Energy is defined as:F = - \ln Z

Substituting the approximation into the definition:F \approx - \ln \left( e^{-\Phi(y_0)} \sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{\Phi''(y_0)}} \right) = \Phi(y_0) - \frac{1}{2} \ln \left( \frac{2\pi}{\Phi''(y_0)} \right)

Consider a partition function for a complex variable z = x + iy:Z = \int \frac{dz d\bar{z}}{2\pi i} e^{-S[z, \bar{z}]}

The action includes a mass term and a quartic interaction:S = \epsilon |z|^2 + g |z|^4

where |z|^4 = z^* z z^* z.

We expand \ln(\epsilon + i\phi) assuming small fluctuations |i\phi| \ll \epsilon:\ln(\epsilon + i\phi) = \ln \left[ \epsilon \left( 1 + \frac{i\phi}{\epsilon} \right) \right] = \ln \epsilon + \ln \left( 1 + \frac{i\phi}{\epsilon} \right)

Using the Taylor series \ln(1+x) \approx x - \frac{x^2}{2}:\ln \left( 1 + \frac{i\phi}{\epsilon} \right) \approx \frac{i\phi}{\epsilon} - \frac{1}{2} \left( \frac{i\phi}{\epsilon} \right)^2= \frac{i}{\epsilon}\phi - \frac{1}{2} \frac{-\phi^2}{\epsilon^2} = \frac{i}{\epsilon}\phi + \frac{\phi^2}{2\epsilon^2}

(Note: The quadratic term is positive because i^2 = -1.)

The action now contains anomalous terms like zz and z^*z^*:S_{\text{quad}} = \epsilon z^* z - \Delta^* z z - \Delta z^* z^*

To write this in matrix form, we must treat z and z^* as a vector. We introduce the Nambu Spinor \Psi = \begin{pmatrix} z \\ z^* \end{pmatrix}. Note that for bosons, symmetrization requires care, but the structure is:S_{\text{quad}} = \frac{1}{2} \begin{pmatrix} z^* & z \end{pmatrix} 
\underbrace{\begin{pmatrix} \epsilon & -2\Delta \\ -2\Delta^* & \epsilon \end{pmatrix}}_{\mathbb{M}} 
\begin{pmatrix} z \\ z^* \end{pmatrix}

We define the stiffness A = \frac{\beta}{C g_{\text{eff}}} + \Pi. The stationary point \phi^* is found by:\frac{\partial S}{\partial \phi} = -i\rho_0 + A\phi = 0 \implies \phi^* = i \frac{\rho_0}{A}

Substituting \phi = \phi^* + \delta\phi into the action:S(\phi) = S_0 + \left( -i\rho_0 \phi^* + \frac{1}{2}A (\phi^*)^2 \right) + \frac{1}{2} A (\delta\phi)^2

The term in the brackets is the Hartree Energy shift:\Delta S_{\text{Hartree}} = \frac{\rho_0^2}{A} - \frac{\rho_0^2}{2A} = \frac{\rho_0^2}{2A}

Using F = -\ln Z:F_{\text{RPA}} = S_0 + \underbrace{\frac{\rho_0^2}{2(\frac{\beta}{Cg} + \Pi)}}_{\text{Hartree (Energy Cost)}} + \underbrace{\frac{1}{2}\ln\left( \frac{\beta}{Cg} + \Pi \right)}_{\text{Correlation (Entropy)}}

Hartree Term: Represents the energy cost of the static mean field induced by the background density. It is positive for repulsive interactions.

Correlation Term: Represents the entropy of Gaussian fluctuations (screening). It lowers the free energy.

The fermionic action now mixes p_1 and p_2. We write it in vector form \Psi = (\psi_{p_1}, \psi_{p_2})^T:S_{\text{fermion}} = \sum_{\omega_n} \begin{pmatrix} \bar{\psi}_{p_1} & \bar{\psi}_{p_2} \end{pmatrix}
\underbrace{
\begin{pmatrix}
-i\omega_n + \xi_{p_1} & -\bar{M} \\
-M & -i\omega_n + \xi_{p_2}
\end{pmatrix}
}_{\mathcal{G}^{-1}_{\text{exch}}}
\begin{pmatrix}
\psi_{p_1} \\
\psi_{p_2}
\end{pmatrix}

To decouple the quartic term, we define Pairing Operators (analogous to Cooper pairs):\begin{aligned}
\hat{\Delta} &= \psi_{p_2} \psi_{p_1} \\
\hat{\Delta}^\dagger &= \bar{\psi}_{p_1} \bar{\psi}_{p_2}
\end{aligned}

The action is now written in a perfect square form suitable for the HS transformation:S_{\text{int}}^{\text{2-state}} = C g_{\text{eff}} \, \hat{\Delta}^\dagger \hat{\Delta}

Using the complex Hubbard-Stratonovich transformation formula:e^{ - C g_{\text{eff}} \hat{\Delta}^\dagger \hat{\Delta} } \propto \int \mathcal{D}\Delta \mathcal{D}\bar{\Delta} \exp\left[ \frac{|\Delta|^2}{C g_{\text{eff}}} - \left( \bar{\Delta} \psi_{p_2} \psi_{p_1} + \Delta \bar{\psi}_{p_1} \bar{\psi}_{p_2} \right) \right]

This successfully linearizes the fermion interaction by introducing an auxiliary bosonic field \Delta.

Combining all terms above, the partition function Z is the integral over all fermion fields (\psi, \bar{\psi}) and the auxiliary boson field (\Delta, \bar{\Delta}):Z = \int \mathcal{D}\Delta \mathcal{D}\bar{\Delta} \mathcal{D}\bar{\psi}_{p_1} \mathcal{D}\psi_{p_1} \mathcal{D}\bar{\psi}_{p_2} \mathcal{D}\psi_{p_2} \exp\left( -S_{\text{total}} \right)

With the full explicit action:\begin{aligned}
S_{\text{total}} = \int_0^\beta d\tau \bigg[ \quad
& \underbrace{\bar{\psi}_{p_1} (\partial_\tau + \xi_{p_1}) \psi_{p_1} + \bar{\psi}_{p_2} (\partial_\tau + \xi_{p_2}) \psi_{p_2}}_{\text{Normal Propagation}} \\
&+ \underbrace{\frac{\bar{\Delta} \Delta}{C g_{\text{eff}}}}_{\text{Auxiliary Field Cost}} \\
&- \underbrace{\left( \bar{\Delta} \psi_{p_2} \psi_{p_1} + \Delta \bar{\psi}_{p_1} \bar{\psi}_{p_2} \right)}_{\text{Pair Creation / Annihilation}}
\quad \bigg]
\end{aligned}

If we expand in Matsubara frequencies (\partial_\tau \to -i\omega_n), the action becomes a sum over n:\begin{aligned}
S_{\text{total}} = \frac{\beta |\Delta|^2}{C g_{\text{eff}}} + \sum_{n} \bigg[ \quad
& \bar{\psi}_{p_1, n} (-i\omega_n + \xi_{p_1}) \psi_{p_1, n} \\
+ \, & \bar{\psi}_{p_2, n} (-i\omega_n + \xi_{p_2}) \psi_{p_2, n} \\
- \, & \bar{\Delta} \psi_{p_2, -n} \psi_{p_1, n} - \Delta \bar{\psi}_{p_1, n} \bar{\psi}_{p_2, -n}
\quad \bigg]
\end{aligned}

(Assuming \Delta is static/constant for simplicity here, otherwise \Delta would carry frequency transfer).

Let’s look at the action for a single frequency n. We group all terms containing \psi_{p_1} or \bar{\psi}_{p_1}:S_{\text{total}} = S_{p_1} + S_{p_2}

Where S_{p_1} contains all the dependence on particle 1:S_{p_1} = \bar{\psi}_{p_1} \underbrace{(-i\omega_n + \xi_{p_1})}_{A_1} \psi_{p_1} - \Delta \bar{\psi}_{p_1} \bar{\psi}_{p_2} - \bar{\Delta} \psi_{p_2} \psi_{p_1}

And S_{p_2} is the remaining term for particle 2:S_{p_2} = \bar{\psi}_{p_2} (-i\omega_{-n} + \xi_{p_2}) \psi_{p_2}

To integrate \int \mathcal{D}\bar{\psi}_{p_1} \mathcal{D}\psi_{p_1} e^{-S_{p_1}}, we need to rewrite the interaction terms as “sources” (\eta) coupled to the fields.

We need the form \bar{\psi}_{p_1} \eta + \bar{\eta} \psi_{p_1}.

Term 1: - \Delta \bar{\psi}_{p_1} \bar{\psi}_{p_2} = \bar{\psi}_{p_1} \underbrace{(-\Delta \bar{\psi}_{p_2})}_{\eta}

Term 2: - \bar{\Delta} \psi_{p_2} \psi_{p_1} = + \bar{\Delta} \psi_{p_1} \psi_{p_2} = \underbrace{(\bar{\Delta} \psi_{p_2})}_{\bar{\eta}} \psi_{p_1}
(Note: We swapped \psi_{p_2} and \psi_{p_1} causing a sign change, then grouped to the left).

So the action for p_1 is:S_{p_1} = \bar{\psi}_{p_1} A_1 \psi_{p_1} + \bar{\psi}_{p_1} \eta + \bar{\eta} \psi_{p_1}

With sources:

\eta = -\Delta \bar{\psi}_{p_2}

\bar{\eta} = \bar{\Delta} \psi_{p_2}

Using the Gaussian shift formula \int e^{-(\bar{\psi} A \psi + \bar{\psi} \eta + \bar{\eta} \psi)} = \det(A) e^{\bar{\eta} A^{-1} \eta}:\int \mathcal{D}\bar{\psi}_{p_1} \mathcal{D}\psi_{p_1} e^{-S_{p_1}} = \det(A_1) \exp\left( \bar{\eta} A_1^{-1} \eta \right)

Now we calculate the shift term \bar{\eta} A_1^{-1} \eta which will be added to the action of p_2.\begin{aligned}
\text{Shift} &= (\bar{\Delta} \psi_{p_2}) \frac{1}{-i\omega_n + \xi_{p_1}} (-\Delta \bar{\psi}_{p_2}) \\
&= - \frac{|\Delta|^2}{-i\omega_n + \xi_{p_1}} \psi_{p_2} \bar{\psi}_{p_2}
\end{aligned}

We swap \psi_{p_2} and \bar{\psi}_{p_2} to match standard order (adding a minus sign):\text{Shift} = + \frac{|\Delta|^2}{-i\omega_n + \xi_{p_1}} \bar{\psi}_{p_2} \psi_{p_2}

Now we construct the effective action for the remaining fermion p_2.
The total coefficient for \bar{\psi}_{p_2} \psi_{p_2} is the original kinetic term plus the new shift term derived above.S_{\text{eff}}^{(p_2)} = \bar{\psi}_{p_2} \underbrace{\left[ (i\omega_n + \xi_{p_2}) + \frac{|\Delta|^2}{-i\omega_n + \xi_{p_1}} \right]}_{A_{\text{new}}} \psi_{p_2}

(Note: -i\omega_{-n} became i\omega_n).

Now, integrate out \psi_{p_2}:\int \mathcal{D}\bar{\psi}_{p_2} \mathcal{D}\psi_{p_2} e^{-S_{\text{eff}}^{(p_2)}} = \det(A_{\text{new}})

The partition function is now a path integral over the complex scalar field \Delta:Z = \int \mathcal{D}\Delta \mathcal{D}\bar{\Delta} \exp\left( - S_{\text{eff}}[\Delta] \right)

Combining the original quadratic cost term and the contribution from the fermion determinant derived in the previous steps:S_{\text{eff}}[\Delta] = S_{\text{condense}} + S_{\text{fluct}}

This comes from the Hubbard-Stratonovich transformation itself:S_{\text{condense}} = \frac{\beta |\Delta|^2}{C g_{\text{eff}}}

This term represents the free energy of the fermions moving in the background of the \Delta field. Using the identity \det(A) = \exp(\text{Tr} \ln A), or simply summing the log of the determinant eigenvalues we found:S_{\text{fluct}} = - \sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty} \ln \left[ (\omega_n^2 + \xi_{p_1} \xi_{p_2} + |\Delta|^2) + i\omega_n(\xi_{p_2} - \xi_{p_1}) \right]

(Note: We used the result \det = (i\omega - \xi_1)(i\omega + \xi_2) - |\Delta|^2 and simplified signs inside the log).

We have the following Hamiltonian:H = \sum_{i=1}^N \varepsilon_\mathbf{k} c

where p_i is the momentum of the i-th particle, and m is the mass of the particle.

The ground state is of course not free electrons. It is an interesting coherent state where particle number is not definite.

It is constructed as follows:\lvert \psi_{BCS \rangle} = e^{\sum_{k} \phi_{k} c_{k\uparrow}^\dagger c_{-k\downarrow}^\dagger} \lvert 0 \rangle

We can not create two electrons with the same spin and momentum so the exponential term is truncated to its 1st order.\lvert \psi_{BCS \rangle} = \prod_{k} \left(1 + \phi_{k} c_{k\uparrow}^\dagger c_{-k\downarrow}^\dagger\right) \lvert 0 \rangle

Given different Cooper pair wave functions \lvert \phi_k \rangle, we can construct different kinds of ground states. We notice that this ground state is not normalized.\braket{\psi_{BCS}}{\psi_{BCS}} = \prod_{k} \langle 0 \vert 1 + \phi^*_{k \rangle c_{-k\downarrow} c_{k\uparrow}} \braket{1 + \phi_{k} c_{k\uparrow}^\dagger c_{-k\downarrow}^\dagger}{0}

NOTICE: It’s free to move (1 + \phi_{k} c_{k\uparrow}^\dagger c_{-k\downarrow}^\dagger) as long as we keep the order of items with the same momentum.

It’s convenient to define creation and annihilation of Cooper pairs as follows:b_{k}^\dagger \equiv c_{k\uparrow}^\dagger c_{-k\downarrow}^\dagger

Of course, vice versa:b_{k} \equiv c_{-k\downarrow} c_{k\uparrow}

We can rewrite the ground state as follows:\lvert \psi_{BCS \rangle} = \prod_{k} \left(1 + \phi_{k} b_{k}^\dagger\right) \lvert 0 \rangle

We can prove the commutation relation of b_{k} and b_{k}^\dagger as follows:[b_{k}, b_{k'}^\dagger] = \delta_{k, k'}[(1-b_{k}), (1-b_{k'}^\dagger)] = \delta_{k, k'}

So Cooper pair is a boson.

We go back to the normalization of the ground state:\begin{align}

    \braket{\psi_{BCS}}{\psi_{BCS}} & = \prod_{k} \langle 0 \vert 1 + \phi^*_{k \rangle b_{k}} \braket{1 + \phi_{k} b_{k}^\dagger}{0} \\
    & = \prod_{k} \langle 0 \rvert 1 + \cancel{\phi^*_{k} b_{k}} + \cancel{\phi_{k} b_{k}^\dagger} + \phi_{k} \phi^*_{k} b_{k} b_{k}^\dagger \lvert 0 \rangle \\
    & = \prod_{k} \langle 0 \vert 1 + \phi_{k \rangle \phi^*_{k} (1 - \cancel{b_{k}^\dagger b_{k}})} \lvert 0 \rangle \\
    & = \prod_{k} (1 + \phi^2_{k})

\end{align}

Based on that we can get the expectation value of Cooper pair creation/annihilation operator:\begin{align}

    \langle \psi_{BCS \rvert} b_{k}^\dagger \lvert \psi_{BCS \rangle} & = \langle 0 \rvert \prod_{k'} \left(1 + \phi^*_{k'} b_{k'}\right) b_{k}^\dagger \prod_{k''} \left(1 + \phi_{k''} b_{k''}^\dagger\right) \lvert 0 \rangle \\
    & = \langle 0 \rvert \left(1 + \phi^*_{k} b_{k} \right) b^\dagger_{k} \prod_{k'\neq k} \left(1 + \phi^*_{k'} b_{k'}\right) \prod_{k''} \left(1 + \phi_{k''} b_{k''}^\dagger\right) \lvert 0 \rangle \\
    & = \langle 0 \rvert \left( \cancel{1} + \phi^*_{k} b_{k} \right) b^\dagger_{k} \left( 1 + \cancel{\phi_{k} b^\dagger_{k}} \right) \prod_{k'\neq k} \left(1 + \phi^*_{k'} b_{k'}\right) \left(1 + \phi_{k'} b_{k'}^\dagger\right)\lvert 0 \rangle \\
    & = \langle 0 \rvert \left(\phi^*_{k} \right) \left( 1 - \cancel{ b^\dagger_{k}  b_{k}} \right) \prod_{k'\neq k} \left(1 + \phi^*_{k'} b_{k'}\right) \left(1 + \phi_{k'} b_{k'}^\dagger\right)\lvert 0 \rangle \\
    & = \phi^*_{k} \prod_{k'\neq k} \left(1 + \phi^2_{k'}\right)  \\

\end{align}

Similarly, we can get the expectation value of b_{k}:\begin{align}

    \langle \psi_{BCS \rvert} b_{k} \lvert \psi_{BCS \rangle} & = \langle 0 \rvert \prod_{k'} \left(1 + \phi^*_{k'} b_{k'}\right) b_{k} \prod_{k''} \left(1 + \phi_{k''} b_{k''}^\dagger\right) \lvert 0 \rangle \\
    & = \langle 0 \rvert \prod_{k'} \left(1 + \phi^*_{k'} b_{k'}\right) \prod_{k''\neq k} \left(1 + \phi_{k''} b_{k''}^\dagger\right) b_{k} \left(\cancel{1} + \phi_{k} b_{k}^\dagger\right)\lvert 0 \rangle \\
    & = \langle 0 \rvert \prod_{k'\neq k} \left(1 + \phi^*_{k'} b_{k'}\right) \prod_{k''\neq k} \left(1 + \phi_{k''} b_{k''}^\dagger\right) \left(1 + \cancel{\phi^*_{k} b_{k}}\right) \phi_{k} \left( 1 - \cancel{b_{k}^\dagger b_{k}}\right)\lvert 0 \rangle \\
    & = \phi_{k} \prod_{k'\neq k} \left(1 + \phi^2_{k'}\right)  \\

\end{align}

It might give us a hint that the average of field operator over a coherent state is the wave function.

And we can get a mean-field theory by averaging the 4-point interaction term over Cooper channel.\begin{align}

    \delta(b^\dagger_{k'})\delta(b_{k}) & = (b^\dagger_{k'} - \langle b^\dagger_{k' \rangle})(b_{k} - \langle b_{k \rangle}) \\
    & = b^\dagger_{k'} b_{k} - b^\dagger_{k'} \langle b_{k \rangle} - \langle b^\dagger_{k' \rangle} b_{k} + \langle b^\dagger_{k' \rangle} \langle b_{k \rangle} \\
    & \approx 0

\end{align}

Sob^\dagger_{k'} b_{k} \approx b^\dagger_{k'} \langle b_{k \rangle} + \langle b^\dagger_{k' \rangle} b_{k} - \langle b^\dagger_{k' \rangle} \langle b_{k \rangle}

Giving  \langle b_{k \rangle}   (\langle b^\dagger_{k' \rangle} ) new names as gap function \Delta_{k} (\Delta^*_{k}), we can get the mean-field Hamiltonian:\begin{align}

    H  = & \sum_{\mathbf{k}, \sigma} \varepsilon_{\mathbf{k}} c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma}^\dagger c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma} + V^{\text{e-ph}}_{\mathbf{k}, \mathbf{k'}} c^\dagger_{\mathbf{k}\uparrow} c^\dagger_{\mathbf{k'}\uparrow} c_{-\mathbf{k'}\downarrow} c_{-\mathbf{k}\uparrow} \\
    \xrightarrow{\text{MF}} & \sum_{\mathbf{k}, \sigma} \varepsilon_{\mathbf{k}} c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma}^\dagger c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma} + \sum_{\mathbf{k}} \Delta_{\mathbf{k}} c_{\mathbf{k}\uparrow}^\dagger c_{-\mathbf{k}\downarrow}^\dagger + \Delta^*_{-\mathbf{k}} c_{-\mathbf{k}\downarrow} c_{\mathbf{k}\uparrow} + \Delta^*_{-\mathbf{k}} \Delta_{\mathbf{k}} \\
    \xrightarrow{\text{Nambu Spinor}} & \sum_{\mathbf{k}, \sigma} \Psi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger} (\vec{h}_{\mathbf{k}} \cdot \vec{\tau}) \Psi_{\mathbf{k}} + \Delta^*_{-\mathbf{k}} \Delta_{\mathbf{k}} \\

\end{align}

Now we have the BCS Hamiltonian. We might get the partition function by path integral of the Fermion field for the four-point interaction.

Using Hubbard-Stratonovich transformation, we can trade the four-point interaction of the fermion field for an effective bosonic field coupling with a 2-point fermion field.

Firstly, the path integral of the fermion field is:Z = \int \mathcal{D} \bar{c^\dagger} \mathcal{D} c \exp 
    \left( \sum_{\mathbf{k}, \sigma} \varepsilon_{\mathbf{k}} c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma}^\dagger c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma} + \sum_{\mathbf{k}, \mathbf{k'}} V_{\mathbf{k}, \mathbf{k'}} c_{\mathbf{k}\uparrow}^\dagger c_{-\mathbf{k'}\downarrow}^\dagger c_{-\mathbf{k}\downarrow} c_{\mathbf{k'}\uparrow} \right)

If we don’t do a mean-field but directly expand the exponential function with respect to the 4-point interaction term. We will get a series:\begin{align}

    Z = \int \mathcal{D} \bar{c^\dagger} \mathcal{D} c 
    \frac{\left(\sum_{\mathbf{k}, \mathbf{k'}} V_{\mathbf{k}, \mathbf{k'}} c_{\mathbf{k}\uparrow}^\dagger c_{-\mathbf{k'}\downarrow}^\dagger c_{-\mathbf{k}\downarrow} c_{\mathbf{k'}\uparrow}\right)^n}{n!} 
    \exp \left( \sum_{\mathbf{k}, \sigma} \varepsilon_{\mathbf{k}} c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma}^\dagger c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma} \right)

\end{align}

Using the functional derivative we convert the functional average into a derivative of Gaussian integral with analytical expression.\begin{align}

    \frac{\delta}{\delta \bar{j_{\mathbf{k}\sigma}^\dagger}} \int \mathcal{D} \bar{c^\dagger} \mathcal{D} c \exp \left( \sum_{\mathbf{k}} \varepsilon_{\mathbf{k}} c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma}^\dagger c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma} + \sum_{\mathbf{k}} j_{\mathbf{k}\sigma} c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma} + \sum_{\mathbf{k}} j_{\mathbf{k}\sigma}^\dagger c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma}^\dagger \right) 
    =
    \frac{\delta}{\delta \bar{j_{\mathbf{k}\sigma}^\dagger}} exp \left( \sum_{\mathbf{k}} \varepsilon_{\mathbf{k}^-1} j_{\mathbf{k}\sigma}^\dagger j_{\mathbf{k}\sigma} \right)

\end{align}

From this kind of unperturbed Hamiltonian and linear coupling we can’t get finite average of Cooper pair amplitude.

But if we write the coupling in the quadratic form, we can get a finite average of Cooper pair amplitude.\begin{align}

    \frac{\delta}{\delta \Delta_{\mathbf{k}}} 
    \exp 
    \left( 
        \sum_{\mathbf{k}}
        \varepsilon_{\mathbf{k}} c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma}^\dagger c_{\mathbf{k}\sigma} +
        \Delta_{\mathbf{k}}^\dagger c_{\mathbf{k}\uparrow}^\dagger c_{-\mathbf{k}\downarrow}^\dagger +
        \Delta_{\mathbf{k}} c_{\mathbf{k}\uparrow} c_{-\mathbf{k}\downarrow} 
        \right)

\end{align}

Now that we have a Hamiltonian of quadratic form, we can write it in a matrix form.

If we define Nambu spinors and write this Hamiltonian on this basis, it would be easy to diagonalize it and get the eigen pairs.\begin{align}

    \Psi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger} = \begin{pmatrix} c_{\mathbf{k}\uparrow}^{\dagger} & c_{-\mathbf{k}\downarrow} \end{pmatrix},
    \Psi_{\mathbf{k}} = \begin{pmatrix} c_{\mathbf{k}\uparrow} \\ c_{-\mathbf{k}\downarrow}^\dagger \end{pmatrix}

\end{align}

Diagonalizing the Hamiltonian will give us the eigen states (the supreconducting state) and the ground state energy of the system.

Gap function is obtained by minimizing the free energy.\Delta_{k} = -\sum_{\mathbf{k'}} V_{\mathbf{k}, \mathbf{k'}} \left( \frac{\Delta_{\mathbf{k'}}}{2 E_{\mathbf{k'}}} \text{tanh}(\frac{\beta E_{\mathbf{k'}}}{2})\right)

where E is the ground state energy, \mu is the chemical potential, N is the number of particles, and \Delta_{k} is the gap function.

It is a bit un-intuitive to understand the meaning of the Nambu spinors.

For normal spinors like Dirac spinors, it’s a 4 component vector where different
entry represents the wavefunction of particle anti-particle with spin up/down.

For Nambu spinors, it’s a 2 component vector where different
entry represents the wavefunction of particle with spin up/down.

But Nambu spinor is a vector of operators. Straightforwardly, we might think well it can
generate a 2-component wavefunction upon operatoring on the vacuum state.

Anyway, we might write the Hamiltonian as a 2\times2 matrix.

We do it step by step, firstly we write the creation and annihilation operators in the Nambu basis.\begin{align}

    c_{k}^\dagger c_{-k}^\dagger & = \Psi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger} \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \Psi_{\mathbf{k'}} \\
    c_{ -k} c_{k} & = \Psi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger} \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 \\ 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \Psi_{\mathbf{k'}} \\

\end{align}

We all know that 2-dimensional traceless unitary matrix is a vector space.

There basis are the very well-known Pauli matrices. We cite it here for convenience.\begin{align}

    \sigma_x / \sigma_1= \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix},
    \sigma_y / \sigma_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & -i \\ i & 0 \end{pmatrix},
    \sigma_z / \sigma_3 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix}

\end{align}

We can define creation and annihilation operators based on the Pauli matrices.\begin{align}

    \sigma_+ = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \left( \sigma_1 + i \sigma_2 \right) = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \\
    \sigma_- = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \left( \sigma_1 - i \sigma_2 \right) = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 0 \\ 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \\

\end{align}

So the creation and annihilation operators can be written as:\begin{align}

    c_{k}^\dagger c_{-k}^\dagger & = \Psi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger} \sigma_+ \Psi_{\mathbf{k}} \\
    c_{ -k} c_{k} & = \Psi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger} \sigma_- \Psi_{\mathbf{k}} \\

\end{align}

We can then write the BCS ground state as:\begin{align}

    \lvert \psi_{BCS \rangle} = \prod_{k} \left(1 + \phi_{k} \sigma_+\right) \lvert 0 \rangle \\

\end{align}

We can write the Hamiltonian in the Nambu basis as:\begin{align}

    H & = \sum_{k} \varepsilon_{k} \Psi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger} \Psi_{\mathbf{k}} + \sum_{k} \Delta_{k} \Psi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger} \sigma_+ \Psi_{\mathbf{k}} + \Delta^*_{-k} \Psi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger} \sigma_- \Psi_{\mathbf{k}} + \Delta^*_{-k} \Delta_{k} \\
      & = \sum_{k} \Psi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger} (\varepsilon_{k} \sigma_0 + \Delta_{k} \sigma_+ + \Delta^*_{-k} \sigma_- ) \Psi_{\mathbf{k}} + \Delta^*_{-k} \Delta_{k} \\

\end{align}

It will be more convenient to write it in Pauli matrix basis instead of creation/annihilation operators.

But refactoring it won’t be a big job. Just separate the real and imaginary parts.\begin{align}

    H & = \sum_{k} \Psi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger} (\varepsilon_{k} \sigma_0 + \mathrm{Re}(\Delta_{k}) \sigma_1 + \mathrm{Im}(\Delta_{k}) \sigma_2 ) \Psi_{\mathbf{k}} + \mathrm{Re}(\Delta^*_{k}) \mathrm{Im}(\Delta_{k}) \\

\end{align}

Of course the ground state is determined by \Delta_{k}. Then Delta_{k} is again a expection value on ground state.

So this leads to a self-consistent equation for \Delta_{k}.

But we will firstly make some comments on the Hamiltonian.

Firstly, if there is no gap, the Hamiltonian is just the free-particle Hamiltonian.

However we can still evaluate the Hamiltonian on coherent state.

We know that for normal spinors, we usually make \sigma_3 commute with the Hamiltonian.

Hence the eigen states of \sigma_3 are the eigen states of the system.

For the Nambu spinors, we can connect \sigma_3 with \sigma_0 by a unitary transformation.\begin{align}

    \sigma_{3k} & = \Psi_{\mathbf{k}}^{\dagger} \sigma_3 \Psi_{\mathbf{k}} \\
     & = (c_{k}^\dagger c_{k} - c_{-k} c_{-k}^\dagger) \\
     & = n_k + n_{-k} - 1 \\

\end{align}

We notice that ground state and Cooper pair states are both eigenstates of \sigma_3.

They happens to have eigenvalues \pm 1.

We find this correspondance between spinors and Nambu spinors.

These two eigen vectors spans the mixture of ground state and Cooper pair states.

For any kind of \Delta_{k}, we can always find a unitary transformation to diagonalize the Hamiltonian.

One may solve the Dyson equation of the Nambu-Gor’kov equation to get the interacting Green’s function,\begin{align}

    \hat{G}^{-1}(\mathbf{k}, \omega) & = \hat{G_0}^{-1}(\mathbf{k}, \omega) - \hat{\Sigma}(\mathbf{k}, \omega) \\
     & = \hat{G_0}^{-1}(\mathbf{k}, \omega) - \hat{\tau_3} \hat{G_0}  \hat{\tau_3} D(\mathbf{k}, \omega) \\

\end{align}
